  "prompt": "Does a voltmeter show RMS voltage?",
  "response": "A standard voltmeter is typically designed to measure RMS (Root Mean Square) voltage when dealing with AC (alternating current) signals. The RMS value is a useful measure for AC because it provides a direct comparison to DC (direct current) voltages in terms of the power they can deliver. When you see a reading on an AC voltmeter, it usually represents the RMS voltage unless otherwise specified.\n\nFor AC voltages, this is important because the voltage is constantly changing over time. The RMS value is essentially the equivalent DC voltage that would provide the same power to a resistive load.\n\nHowever, it's worth noting that this holds true primarily for sinusoidal waveforms. For non-sinusoidal waveforms, a standard AC voltmeter may not provide an accurate RMS reading unless it is specifically a true RMS voltmeter. A true RMS voltmeter can measure the RMS value of both sinusoidal and non-sinusoidal waveforms accurately.",
